{"name":"Log","hostname":"localhost","pid":16128,"level":30,"req":{"meta":{"requestId":"db21a1e0-f06f-11e7-b951-c1a9cf7ca6a4","userId":null},"url":"/2017/12/28/wordpress-on-aws-part-1/","method":"GET","originalUrl":"/2017/12/28/wordpress-on-aws-part-1/","params":{"0":"/2017/12/28/wordpress-on-aws-part-1/"},"headers":{"x-forwarded-for":"66.249.70.22","x-forwarded-proto":"https","x-real-ip":"66.249.70.22","host":"bmonsalvatge.com","connection":"close","accept":"text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,*/*;q=0.8","from":"googlebot(at)googlebot.com","user-agent":"Mozilla/5.0 (compatible; Googlebot/2.1; +http://www.google.com/bot.html)","accept-encoding":"gzip,deflate,br","if-modified-since":"Mon, 01 Jan 2018 16:45:39 GMT"},"body":{},"query":{}},"res":{"_headers":{"x-powered-by":"Express","cache-control":"public, max-age=0","content-type":"text/html; charset=utf-8","etag":"W/\"665a-Qzm8R5+bA+fIbo/+o7BbadfQfU0\"","vary":"Accept-Encoding","content-encoding":"gzip"},"statusCode":200,"responseTime":"73ms"},"msg":"","time":"2018-01-03T10:21:26.730Z","v":0}
{"name":"Log","hostname":"localhost","pid":16128,"level":30,"req":{"meta":{"requestId":"24186a40-f071-11e7-b951-c1a9cf7ca6a4","userId":null},"url":"/","method":"GET","originalUrl":"/2017/12/28/wordpress-on-aws-part-1/amp/","params":{},"headers":{"x-forwarded-for":"66.249.70.20","x-forwarded-proto":"https","x-real-ip":"66.249.70.20","host":"bmonsalvatge.com","connection":"close","accept":"text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,*/*;q=0.8","from":"googlebot(at)googlebot.com","user-agent":"Mozilla/5.0 (Linux; Android 6.0.1; Nexus 5X Build/MMB29P) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/41.0.2272.96 Mobile Safari/537.36 (compatible; Googlebot/2.1; +http://www.google.com/bot.html)","accept-encoding":"gzip,deflate,br"},"body":{"post":{"slug":"wordpress-on-aws-part-1","status":"published","id":"5a45b548e32546392fdbaafd","uuid":"56039a8b-8a04-4f3e-b313-16348cad53b9","title":"WordPress on AWS - Part 1","html":"<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p>Today I am going to go over setting up WordPress (4.8.2 at the time of writing) on AWS using EC2 and RDS (MariaDB).  This will be a pretty straightforward way of getting setup on AWS with a new WordPress site.   In this tutorial we will not be diving into a multiple availability zone setup, however this will be a topic I dive into later.  All services spun up in this tutorial will exist within the AWS free tier!</p>\n<hr>\n<h1 id=\"creatingtheec2instance\">Creating the EC2 Instance</h1>\n<p>First log into your AWS console and go to the EC2 section.  Select the Amazon Linux AMI (2017.03.1) and for instance type select t2.micro instance (free-tier eligible).   Next let's go to &quot;Configure Instance Details&quot;.  We're not going to anything here, however it's a good idea to know what exact you're spinning up:</p>\n<p><img src=\"/content/images/2017/12/Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-6.55.13-PM.png\" alt=\"Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-6.55.13-PM\"></p>\n<p><strong>Network</strong> - Which VPC network our  EC2 instance will be connected to.  It is important that if you use a non-default VPC that this EC2 instance and our RDS instance are in the same VPC for private network connectivity.</p>\n<p>Everything can remain default here, we don't need to specify a subnet as we are not creating a multi-az setup.  Let's continue.</p>\n<h2 id=\"addstorage\">Add Storage</h2>\n<p><img src=\"/content/images/2017/12/Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-6.59.44-PM.png\" alt=\"Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-6.59.44-PM\"></p>\n<p>We're going to keep this as default, we really won't need too much to start a WordPress site, and if we do we can use S3 for some of that later (will make a tutorial on integrated S3 later).</p>\n<p>Afterwards we will add our tags, however this is optional and more to keep your instances organized in the AWS Console.</p>\n<h2 id=\"securitywebdmz\">Security - WebDMZ</h2>\n<p>Here is where we are going to create our web server's security group.  Here we will want to allow inbound traffic over the following ports:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>22 -- SSH:  You have the option of scoping this down to your own IP, however if you do not have a static IP on your local connection you'll have to update this via the AWS Console every time you want to SSH.</li>\n<li>80 &amp; 433 -- HTTP / HTTPS:  This is to allow anyone to reach our web server.</li>\n<li>20-21 -- FTP:  We will need this in order to upload themes, plugins, and files to WordPress as it relies on an underlying FTP server.</li>\n<li>1024-1048 -- PASV Ports for FTP:  We'll specify this later in our &quot;vsftp&quot; configuration.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><img src=\"/content/images/2017/12/Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-10.05.09-PM.png\" alt=\"Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-10.05.09-PM\"></p>\n<h2 id=\"reviewandlaunch\">Review and Launch</h2>\n<p>Now we're going to review and launch our EC2 instance.  Once we go to launch, we will be presented with an option to create a &quot;Key Pair&quot;.  We will need this to SSH into our EC2 instance.  So give it some name and save it to your local computer.  I typically recommend placing it into your local computer's user folder under a folder called SSH (useful if you have lots of SSH Keys).</p>\n<p><img src=\"/content/images/2017/12/Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-10.14.42-PM.png\" alt=\"Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-10.14.42-PM\"></p>\n<p><strong>Then launch!</strong></p>\n<hr>\n<p>Congrats you've spun up the thing that's going to be hosting our site files and serving web traffic.  Next we'll be creating the RDS instance, which is where we'll keep our WordPress database.</p>\n</div>","feature_image":"/content/images/2017/12/Untitled-3.png","featured":false,"page":false,"locale":null,"visibility":"public","meta_title":"WordPress on AWS - Part 1","meta_description":"Today I am going to go over setting up WordPress on AWS using EC2 and RDS.  This will be a pretty straightforward way of getting setup on AWS!","created_at":{},"created_by":"1","updated_at":{},"updated_by":"1","published_at":{},"published_by":"1","custom_excerpt":"Today I am going to go over setting up WordPress (4.8.2 at the time of writing) on AWS using EC2 and RDS (MariaDB).  This will be a pretty straightforward way of getting setup on AWS with a new WordPress site.   In this tutorial we will not be diving into a multiple availability zone setup.","codeinjection_head":"","codeinjection_foot":"","og_image":null,"og_title":null,"og_description":null,"twitter_image":null,"twitter_title":null,"twitter_description":null,"custom_template":null,"tags":{"0":{"id":"5a45b7a2e32546392fdbaafe","name":"Wordpress","slug":"wordpress","description":null,"feature_image":null,"visibility":"public","meta_title":null,"meta_description":null,"created_at":{},"created_by":"1","updated_at":{},"updated_by":"1","parent":null},"1":{"id":"5a45b7a2e32546392fdbaaff","name":"tutorial","slug":"tutorial","description":null,"feature_image":null,"visibility":"public","meta_title":null,"meta_description":null,"created_at":{},"created_by":"1","updated_at":{},"updated_by":"1","