ng command (Terminal on Mac or Linux, and I recommend cmder on Windows):\\n\\n`ssh -i mykeylocation.pem ec2-user@mypublicipaddress`\\n\\nIf you're on a Mac you may get a warning about permissions.  To fix this you must run the follow command to change the permissions level of your private key:\\n\\n`chmod 400 mykeylocation.pem`\\n\\nOnce connect let's elevate to root privileges for this setup (we'll fix the permissions of our website specifically afterwards).\\n\\n`sudo su -`\\n\\n## Installing Software\\n\\nNow that we're logged in let's run the following commands to get all the necessary software onto our EC2 instance.\\n\\n`yum install httpd24`\\n`yum install php70`\\n`yum install php70-mysql*`\\n\\nYou can skip this next step if you would rather connect to your RDS instance using a database tool to create the WordPress user and Database.\\n\\n`yum install mysql`\\n\\nWe will also want to install our FTP service.  For this tutorial we'll use vsftp:\\n\\n`yum install vsftpd`\\n\\nNow we will want to make sure when we turn on our instance that Apache is started, so let's run the following command:\\n\\n`chkconfig httpd on`\\n\\n## Configuring Our Software\\n\\nNow that we have everything we need installed, let's tweak some settings around.\\n\\n### HTTP\\n\\nFirst thing since WordPress uses index.php as its main entry point we will need to make sure Apache knows that.  Let's edit our Apache config by running the following:\\n\\n`vim /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf`\\n\\nFind the following block of code:\\n\\n*place holder*\\n\\nI've already added it here, but you will want to make sure index.php is added, otherwise Apache will not look to load it, and you're WordPress site won't load.\\n\\n### VSFTP\\n\\nHere we'll want to open our configuration file:\\n\\n`vim /etc/vsftpd/vsftpd.conf`\\n\\nWe will first want to uncomment and change \\\"chroot_local_user\\\" and change it \\\"chroot_local_user=YES\\\".  This will prevent our FTP user we're about to create from accessing our entire system.\\n\\nThere we will want to change \\\"anonymous_enable=YES\\\" to \\\"anonymous_enable=NO\\\". Then let's go down to the bottom of our file and add the following code:\\n\\n```\\npasv_enable=YES\\npasv_min_port=1024\\npasv_max_port=1048\\npasv_address=ec2instancePublicIP\\n```\\n\\nLet's save and restart the service:\\n\\n`/etc/init.d/vsftpd restart`\\n\\n### Creating our Linux User for Apache & FTP\\n\\nNow we're going to create a user which we will user for our WordPress site, to log into FTP.\\n\\n`adduser wpuser`\\n\\nThen we will set the password (make sure to save this) for our new user.\\n\\n`passwd wpuser`\\n\\nNow as mentioned before, we've prevent our ftp user from accessing our entire system, so we'll want to change its home directory. To do that we will run:\\n\\n`usermod -d /var/www/html/ wpuser`\\n\\nThis will set our wpuser home directory to the location where we will be serving our WordPress blog.\\n\\n## Downloading and Setting up WordPress\\n\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}","page":false,"plaintext":"","slug":"wordpress-on-aws-part-3","status":"draft","title":"WordPress on AWS - Part 3","updated_at":"2018-01-03T22:10:02.000Z","updated_by":"1","tags":{},"author_id":"1"}}},"query":{"include":"tags"}},"res":{"_headers":{"x-powered-by":"Express","cache-control":"no-cache, private, no-store, must-revalidate, max-stale=0, post-check=0, pre-check=0","access-control-allow-origin":"https://bmonsalvatge.com","vary":"Origin, Accept-Encoding","x-cache-invalidate":"/p/628d6232-ea4c-41e1-822c-c6d3462b4c17/","content-type":"application/json; charset=utf-8","etag":"W/\"13fd-J+ZnOxLZEnJbLbeJd1nQ36MOxU0\"","content-encoding":"gzip"},"statusCode":200,"responseTime":"172ms"},"msg":"","time":"2018-01-03T22:10:25.343Z","v":0}
{"name":"Log","hostname":"localhost","pid":16128,"level":30,"req":{"meta":{"requestId":"ef68a320-f0d2-11e7-b951-c1a9cf7ca6a4","userId":"1"},"url":"/posts/5a4d5340fd55d33f00065ad5/?include=tags","method":"PUT","originalUrl":"/ghost/api/v0.1/posts/5a4d5340fd55d33f00065ad5/?include=tags","params":{"id":"5a4d5340fd55d33f00065ad5"},"headers":{"x-forwarded-for":"67.8.27.65","x-forwarded-proto":"https","x-real-ip":"67.8.27.65","host":"bmonsalvatge.com","connection":"close","content-length":"5313","origin":"https://bmonsalvatge.com","app-pragma":"no-cache","content-type":"application/json; charset=UTF-8","accept":"application/json, text/javascript, */*; q=0.01","x-requested-with":"XMLHttpRequest","x-ghost-version":"1.19","user-agent":"Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/63.0.3239.84 Safari/537.36","referer":"https://bmonsalvatge.com/ghost/","accept-encoding":"gzip, deflate, br","accept-language":"en-US,en;q=0.9"},"body":{"posts":{"0":{"id":"5a4d5340fd55d33f00065ad5","created_at":"2018-01-03T22:03:44.000Z","featured":false,"codeinjection_foot":"","codeinjection_head":"","mobiledoc":"{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"# Setting Up Our Web Instance\\n\\nWe will be configuring our web VM with Apache 2.4, PHP 7.0.  In addition, for simplicity, we will install the default MySQL package on our VM as this will allow us to later connect to our RDS instance and create the WP User and Database for our site.\\n\\nFirst let's SSH into our EC2 instance.  To do this you will need to grab the public IP, or public DNS, of your EC2 instance we just created.  You can do this by selecting your EC2 instance from the \\\"Instances\\\" tab on the left.  You can either drag or select those gray boxes on the right to make the bottom pane larger.\\n\\n*place holder*\\n\\nOnce you have your public IP let's SSH in!  from your favorite SSH tool run the following command (Terminal on Mac or Linux, and I recommend cmder on Windows):\\n\\n`ssh -i mykeylocation.pem ec2-user@mypublicipaddress`\\n\\nIf you're on a Mac you may get a warning about permissions.  To fix this you must run the follow command to change the permissions level of your private key:\\n\\n`chmod 400 mykeylocation.pem`\\n\\nOnce connect let's elevate to root privileges for this setup (we'll fix the permissions of our website specifically afterwards).\\n\\n`sudo su -`\\n\\n## Installing Software\\n\\nNow that we're logged in let's run the following commands to get all the necessary software onto our EC2 instance.\\n\\n`yum install httpd24`\\n`yum install php70`\\n`yum install php70-mysql*`\\n\\nYou can skip this next step if you would rather connect to your RDS instance using a database tool to create the WordPress user and Database.\\n\\n`yum install mysql`\\n\\nWe will also want to install our FTP service.  For this tutorial we'll use vsftp:\\n\\n`yum install vsftpd`\\n\\nNow we will want to make sure when we turn on our instance that Apache is started, so let's run the following command:\\n\\n`chkconfig httpd on`\\n\\n## Configuring Our Software\\n\\nNow that we have everything we need installed, let's tweak some settings around.\\n\\n### HTTP\\n\\nFirst thing since WordPress uses index.php as its main entry point we will need to make sure Apache knows that.  Let's edit our Apache config by running the following:\\n\\n`vim /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf`\\n\\nFind the following block of code:\\n\\n*place holder*\\n\\nI've already added it here, but you will want to make sure index.php is added, otherwise Apache will not look to load it, and you're WordPress site won't load.\\n\\n### VSFTP\\n\\nHere we'll want to open our configuration file:\\n\\n`vim /etc/vsftpd/vsftpd.conf`\\n\\nWe will first want to uncomment and change \\\"chroot_local_user\\\" and change it \\\"chroot_local_user=YES\\\".  This will prevent our FTP user we're about to create from accessing our entire system.\\n\\nThere we will want to change \\\"anonymous_enable=YES\\\" to \\\"anonymous_enable=NO\\\". Then let's go down to the bottom of our file and add the following code:\\n\\n```\\npasv_enable=YES\\npasv_min_port=1024\\npasv_max_port=1048\\npasv_address=ec2instancePublicIP\\n```\\n\\nLet's save and restart the service:\\n\\n`/etc/init.d/vsftpd restart`\\n\\n### Creating our Linux User for Apache & FTP\\n\\nNow we're going to create a user which we will user for our WordPress site, to log into FTP.\\n\\n`adduser wpuser`\\n\\nThen we will set the password (make sure to save this) for our new user.\\n\\n`passwd wpuser`\\n\\nNow as mentioned before, we've prevent our ftp user from accessing our entire system, so we'll want to change its home directory. To do that we will run:\\n\\n`usermod -d /var/www/html/ wpuser`\\n\\nThis will set our wpuser home directory to the location where we will be serving our WordPress blog.\\n\\n## Downloading and Setting up WordPress\\n\\nHere we'll get our WordPress install to \\\"/var/www/html/\\\" and get our permissions setup.  First let's download the latest version of WordPress and extract it to our web folder:\\n\\nwget https://wordpress.org/latest.tar.gz\\ntar -xzf latest.tar.gz\\n\\nNow when we type ls we should see our \\\"wordpress\\\" folder. Let's move its contents into our html folder.\\n\\nmv wordpress/* /var/www/html/\\n\\nNow that we got it at the right location let's change directories there and start working on our site.\\n\\ncd /var/www/html\\n\\nNow that we're here we need to change permissions so that our user and apache can access this folder:\\n\\nchown -R apache:apache /var/www/html\\n\\nThis command will make wpuser the owner and change the group to apache.\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}","page":false,"plaintext":"","slug":"wordpress-on-aws-part-3","status":"draft","title":"WordPress on AWS - Part 3","updated_at":"2018-01-03T22:10:25.000Z","updated_by":"1","tags":{},"author_id":"1"}}},"query":{"include":"tags"}},"res":{"_headers":{"x-powered-by":"Express","cache-control":"no-cache, private, no-store, must-revalidate, max-stale=0, post-check=0, pre-check=0","access-control-allow-origin":"https://bmonsalvatge.com","vary":"Origin, Accept-Encoding","x-cache-invalidate":"/p/628d6232-ea4c-41e1-822c-c6d3462b4c17/","content-type":"application/json; charset=utf-8","etag":"W/\"1754-NWbRbT6TiWzo3jvh4zov0n69CCk\"","content-encoding":"gzip"},"statusCode":200,"responseTime":"174ms"},"msg":"","time":"2018-01-03T22:10:41.030Z","v":0}
{"name":"Log","hostname":"localhost","pid":16128,"level":30,"req":{"meta":{"requestId":"f88825c0-f0d2-11e7-b951-c1a9cf7ca6a4","userId":"1"},"url":"/posts/5a4d5340fd55d33f00065ad5/?include=tags","method":"PUT","originalUrl":"/ghost/api/v0.1/posts/5a4d5340fd55d33f00065ad5/?include=tags","params":{"id":"5a4d5340fd55d33f00065ad5"},"headers":{"x-forwarded-for":"67.8.27.65","x-forwarded-proto":"https","x-real-ip":"67.8.27.65","host":"bmonsalvatge.com","connection":"close","content-length":"5323","origin":"https://bmonsalvatge.com","app-pragma":"no-cache","content-type":"application/json; charset=UTF-8","accept":"application/json, text/javascript, */*; q=0.01","x-requested-with":"XMLHttpRequest","x-ghost-version":"1.19","user-agent":"Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/63.0.3239.84 Safari/537.36","referer":"https://bmonsalvatge.com/ghost/","accept-encoding":"gzip, deflate, br","accept-language":"en-US,en;q=0.9"},"body":{"posts":{"0":{"id":"5a4d5340fd55d33f00065ad5","created_at":"2018-01-03T22:03:44.000Z","featured":false,"codeinjection_foot":"","codeinjection_head":"","mobiledoc":"{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"# Setting Up Our Web Instance\\n\\nWe will be configuring our web VM with Apache 2.4, PHP 7.0.  In addition, for simplicity, we will install the default MySQL package on our VM as this will allow us to later connect to our RDS instance and create the WP User and Database for our site.\\n\\nFirst let's SSH into our EC2 instance.  To do this you will need to grab the public IP, or public DNS, of your EC2 instance we just created.  You can do this by selecting your EC2 instance from the \\\"Instances\\\" tab on the left.  You can either drag or select those gray boxes on the right to make the bottom pane larger.\\n\\n*place holder*\\n\\nOnce you have your public IP let's SSH in!  from your favorite SSH tool run the following command (Terminal on Mac or Linux, and I recommend cmder on Windows):\\n\\n`ssh -i mykeylocation.pem ec2-user@mypublicipaddress`\\n\\nIf you're on a Mac you may get a warning about permissions.  To fix this you must run the follow command to change the permissions level of your private key:\\n\\n`chmod 400 mykeylocation.pem`\\n\\nOnce connect let's elevate to root privileges for this setup (we'll fix the permissions of our website specifically afterwards).\\n\\n`sudo su -`\\n\\n## Installing Software\\n\\nNow that we're logged in let's run the following commands to get all the necessary software onto our EC2 instance.\\n\\n`yum install httpd24`\\n`yum install php70`\\n`yum install php70-mysql*`\\n\\nYou can skip this next step if you would rather connect to your RDS instance using a database tool to create the WordPress user and Database.\\n\\n`yum install mysql`\\n\\nWe will also want to install our FTP service.  For this tutorial we'll use vsftp:\\n\\n`yum install vsftpd`\\n\\nNow we will want to make sure when we turn on our instance that Apache is started, so let's run the following command:\\n\\n`chkconfig httpd on`\\n\\n## Configuring Our Software\\n\\nNow that we have everything we need installed, let's tweak some settings around.\\n\\n### HTTP\\n\\nFirst thing since WordPress uses index.php as its main entry point we will need to make sure Apache knows that.  Let's edit our Apache config by running the following:\\n\\n`vim /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf`\\n\\nFind the following block of code:\\n\\n*place holder*\\n\\nI've already added it here, but you will want to make sure index.php is added, otherwise Apache will not look to load it, and you're WordPress site won't load.\\n\\n### VSFTP\\n\\nHere we'll want to open our configuration file:\\n\\n`vim /etc/vsftpd/vsftpd.conf`\\n\\nWe will first want to uncomment and change \\\"chroot_local_user\\\" and change it \\\"chroot_local_user=YES\\\".  This will prevent our FTP user we're about to create from accessing our entire system.\\n\\nThere we will want to change \\\"anonymous_enable=YES\\\" to \\\"anonymous_enable=NO\\\". Then let's go down to the bottom of our file and add the following code:\\n\\n```\\npasv_enable=YES\\npasv_min_port=1024\\npasv_max_port=1048\\npasv_address=ec2instancePublicIP\\n```\\n\\nLet's save and restart the service:\\n\\n`/etc/init.d/vsftpd restart`\\n\\n### Creating our Linux User for Apache & FTP\\n\\nNow we're going to create a user which we will user for our WordPress site, to log into FTP.\\n\\n`adduser wpuser`\\n\\nThen we will set the password (make sure to save this) for our new user.\\n\\n`passwd wpuser`\\n\\nNow as mentioned before, we've prevent our ftp user from accessing our entire system, so we'll want to change its home directory. To do that we will run:\\n\\n`usermod -d /var/www/html/ wpuser`\\n\\nThis will set our wpuser home directory to the location where we will be serving our WordPress blog.\\n\\n## Downloading and Setting up WordPress\\n\\nHere we'll get our WordPress install to \\\"/var/www/html/\\\" and get our permissions setup.  First let's download the latest version of WordPress and extract it to our web folder:\\n\\n`wget https://wordpress.org/latest.tar.gz`\\n`tar -xzf latest.tar.gz`\\n\\nNow when we type ls we should see our \\\"wordpress\\\" folder. Let's move its contents into our html folder.\\n\\n`mv wordpress/* /var/www/html/`\\n\\nNow that we got it at the right location let's change directories there and start working on our site.\\n\\n`cd /var/www/html`\\n\\nNow that we're here we need to change permissions so that our user and apache can access this folder:\\n\\n`chown -R apache:apache /var/www/html`\\n\\nThis command will make wpuser the owner and change the group to apache.\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}","page":false,"plaintext":"","slug":"wordpress-on-aws-part-3","status":"draft","title":"WordPress on AWS - Part 3","updated_at":"2018-01-03T22:10:40.000Z","updated_by":"1","tags":{},"author_id":"1"}}},"query":{"include":"tags"}},"res":{"_headers":{"x-powered-by":"Express","cache-control":"no-cache, private, no-store, must-revalidate, max-stale=0, post-check=0, pre-check=0","access-control-allow-origin":"https://bmonsalvatge.com","vary":"Origin, Accept-Encoding","x-cache-invalidate":"/p/628d6232-ea4c-41e1-822c-c6d3462b4c17/","content-type":"application/json; charset=utf-8","etag":"W/\"1761-MrnTVWhN9ZglMz9uTgr0QCzvIb0\"","content-encoding":"gzip"},"statusCode":200,"responseTime":"170ms"},"msg":"","time":"2018-01-03T22:10:56.332Z","v":0}
{"name":"Log","hostname":"localhost","pid":16128,"level":30,"req":{"meta":{"requestId":"0c442e10-f0d3-11e7-b951-c1a9cf7ca6a4","userId":"1"},"url":"/posts/5a4d5340fd55d33f00065ad5/?include=tags","method":"PUT","originalUrl":"/ghost/api/v0.1/posts/5a4d5340fd55d33f00065ad5/?include=tags","params":{"id":"5a4d5340fd55d33f00065ad5"},"headers":{"x-forwarded-for":"67.8.27.65","x-forwarded-proto":"https","x-real-ip":"67.8.27.65","host":"bmonsalvatge.com","connection":"close","content-length":"6004","origin":"https://bmonsalvatge.com","app-pragma":"no-cache","content-type":"application/json; charset=UTF-8","accept":"application/json, text/javascript, */*; q=0.01","x-requested-with":"XMLHttpRequest","x-ghost-version":"1.19","user-agent":"Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/63.0.3239.84 Safari/537.36","referer":"https://bmonsalvatge.com/ghost/","accept-encoding":"gzip, deflate, br","accept-language":"en-US,en;q=0.9"},"body":{"posts":{"0":{"id":"5a4d5340fd55d33f00065ad5","created_at":"2018-01-03T22:03:44.000Z","featured":false,"codeinjection_foot":"","codeinjection_head":"","mobiledoc":"{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"# Setting Up Our Web Instance\\n\\nWe will be configuring our web VM with Apache 2.4, PHP 7.0.  In addition, for simplicity, we will install the default MySQL package on our VM as this will allow us to later connect to our RDS instance and create the WP User and Database for our site.\\n\\nFirst let's SSH into our EC2 instance.  To do this you will need to grab the public IP, or public DNS, of your EC2 instance we just created.  You can do this by selecting your EC2 instance from the \\\"Instances\\\" tab on the left.  You can either drag or select those gray boxes on the right to make the bottom pane larger.\\n\\n*place holder*\\n\\nOnce you have your public IP let's SSH in!  from your favorite SSH tool run the following command (Terminal on Mac or Linux, and I recommend cmder on Windows):\\n\\n`ssh -i mykeylocation.pem ec2-user@mypublicipaddress`\\n\\nIf you're on a Mac you may get a warning about permissions.  To fix this you must run the follow command to change the permissions level of your private key:\\n\\n`chmod 400 mykeylocation.pem`\\n\\nOnce connect let's elevate to root privileges for this setup (we'll fix the permissions of our website specifically afterwards).\\n\\n`sudo su -`\\n\\n## Installing Software\\n\\nNow that we're logged in let's run the following commands to get all the necessary software onto our EC2 instance.\\n\\n`yum install httpd24`\\n`yum install php70`\\n`yum install php70-mysql*`\\n\\nYou can skip this next step if you would rather connect to your RDS instance using a database tool to create the WordPress user and Database.\\n\\n`yum install mysql`\\n\\nWe will also want to install our FTP service.  For this tutorial we'll use vsftp:\\n\\n`yum install vsftpd`\\n\\nNow we will want to make sure when we turn on our instance that Apache is started, so let's run the following command:\\n\\n`chkconfig httpd on`\\n\\n## Configuring Our Software\\n\\nNow that we have everything we need installed, let's tweak some settings around.\\n\\n### HTTP\\n\\nFirst thing since WordPress uses index.php as its main entry point we will need to make sure Apache knows that.  Let's edit our Apache config by running the following:\\n\\n`vim /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf`\\n\\nFind the following block of code:\\n\\n*place holder*\\n\\nI've already added it here, but you will want to make sure index.php is added, otherwise Apache will not look to load it, and you're WordPress site won't load.\\n\\n### VSFTP\\n\\nHere we'll want to open our configuration file:\\n\\n`vim /etc/vsftpd/vsftpd.conf`\\n\\nWe will first want to uncomment and change \\\"chroot_local_user\\\" and change it \\\"chroot_local_user=YES\\\".  This will prevent our FTP user we're about to create from accessing our entire system.\\n\\nThere we will want to change \\\"anonymous_enable=YES\\\" to \\\"anonymous_enable=NO\\\". Then let's go down to the bottom of our file and add the following code:\\n\\n```\\npasv_enable=YES\\npasv_min_port=1024\\npasv_max_port=1048\\npasv_address=ec2instancePublicIP\\n```\\n\\nLet's save and restart the service:\\n\\n`/etc/init.d/vsftpd restart`\\n\\n### Creating our Linux User for Apache & FTP\\n\\nNow we're going to create a user which we will user for our WordPress site, to log into FTP.\\n\\n`adduser wpuser`\\n\\nThen we will set the password (make sure to save this) for our new user.\\n\\n`passwd wpuser`\\n\\nNow as mentioned before, we've prevent our ftp user from accessing our entire system, so we'll want to change its home directory. To do that we will run:\\n\\n`usermod -d /var/www/html/ wpuser`\\n\\nThis will set our wpuser home directory to the location where we will be serving our WordPress blog.\\n\\n## Downloading and Setting up WordPress\\n\\nHere we'll get our WordPress install to \\\"/var/www/html/\\\" and get our permissions setup.  First let's download the latest version of WordPress and extract it to our web folder:\\n\\n`wget https://wordpress.org/latest.tar.gz`\\n`tar -xzf latest.tar.gz`\\n\\nNow when we type ls we should see our \\\"wordpress\\\" folder. Let's move its contents into our html folder.\\n\\n`mv wordpress/* /var/www/html/`\\n\\nNow that we got it at the right location let's change directories there and start working on our site.\\n\\n`cd /var/www/html`\\n\\nNow that we're here we need to change permissions so that our user and apache can access this folder:\\n\\n`chown -R apache:apache /var/www/html`\\n\\nThis command will make wpuser the owner and change the group to apache.\\n\\nNow that we have that let's make a copy of the wp-config-sample.php and bring it to our active config and edit it.\\n\\ncp wp-config-sample.php wp-config.php\\nvim wp-config.php\\n\\nThere are 4 variables that we'll be changing there.\\n\\n/** The name of the database for WordPress */\\ndefine('DB_NAME', 'wpblog');\\n\\n/** MySQL database username */\\ndefine('DB_USER', 'wpblogger');\\n\\n/** MySQL database password */\\ndefine('DB_PASSWORD', 'password');\\n\\n/** MySQL hostname */\\ndefine('DB_HOST', 'myrdsprivatehostname');\\nWe'll be create the user and password in just a sec, but you can grab myrdsprivatehostname (Endpoint) from the RDS page in the AWS console.\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}","page":false,"plaintext":"","slug":"wordpress-on-aws-part-3","status":"draft","title":"WordPress on AWS - Part 3","updated_at":"2018-01-03T22:10:56.000Z","updated_by":"1","tags":{},"author_id":"1"}}},"query":{"include":"tags"}},"res":{"_headers":{"x-powered-by":"Express","cache-control":"no-cache, private, no-store, must-revalidate, max-stale=0, post-check=0, pre-check=0","access-control-allow-origin":"https://bmonsalvatge.com","vary":"Origin, Accept-Encoding","x-cache-invalidate":"/p/628d6232-ea4c-41e1-822c-c6d3462b4c17/","content-type":"application/json; charset=utf-8","etag":"W/\"1a31-sqeH0LwMEQVb9kcapN5v1msu9eA\"","content-encoding":"gzip"},"statusCode":200,"responseTime":"176ms"},"msg":"","time":"2018-01-03T22:11:29.449Z","v":0}
{"name":"Log","hostname":"localhost","pid":16128,"level":30,"req":{"meta":{"requestId":"16b69680-f0d3-11e7-b951-c1a9cf7ca6a4","userId":"1"},"url":"/posts/5a4d5340fd55d33f00065ad5/?include=tags","method":"PUT","originalUrl":"/ghost/api/v0.1/posts/5a4d5340fd55d33f00065ad5/?include=tags","params":{"id":"5a4d5340fd55d33f00065ad5"},"headers":{"x-forwarded-for":"67.8.27.65","x-forwarded-proto":"https","x-real-ip":"67.8.27.65","host":"bmonsalvatge.com","connection":"close","content-length":"6042","origin":"https://bmonsalvatge.com","app-pragma":"no-cache","content-type":"application/json; charset=UTF-8","accept":"application/json, text/javascript, */*; q=0.01","x-requested-with":"XMLHttpRequest","x-ghost-version":"1.19","user-agent":"Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/63.0.3239.84 Safari/537.36","referer":"https://bmonsalvatge.com/ghost/","accept-encoding":"gzip, deflate, br","accept-language":"en-US,en;q=0.9"},"body":{"posts":{"0":{"id":"5a4d5340fd55d33f00065ad5","created_at":"2018-01-03T22:03:44.000Z","featured":false,"codeinjection_foot":"","codeinjection_head":"","mobiledoc":"{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"# Setting Up Our Web Instance\\n\\nWe will be configuring our web VM with Apache 2.4, PHP 7.0.  In addition, for simplicity, we will install the default MySQL package on our VM as this will allow us to later connect to our RDS instance and create the WP User and Database for our site.\\n\\nFirst let's SSH into our EC2 instance.  To do this you will need to grab the public IP, or public DNS, of your EC2 instance we just created.  You can do this by selecting your EC2 instance from the \\\"Instances\\\" tab on the left.  You can either drag or select those gray boxes on the right to make the bottom pane larger.\\n\\n*place holder*\\n\\nOnce you have your public IP let's SSH in!  from your favorite SSH tool run the following command (Terminal on Mac or Linux, and I recommend cmder on Windows):\\n\\n`ssh -i mykeylocation.pem ec2-user@mypublicipaddress`\\n\\nIf you're on a Mac you may get a warning about permissions.  To fix this you must run the follow command to change the permissions level of your private key:\\n\\n`chmod 400 mykeylocation.pem`\\n\\nOnce connect let's elevate to root privileges for this setup (we'll fix the permissions of our website specifically afterwards).\\n\\n`sudo su -`\\n\\n## Installing Software\\n\\nNow that we're logged in let's run the following commands to get all the necessary software onto our EC2 instance.\\n\\n`yum install httpd24`\\n`yum install php70`\\n`yum install php70-mysql*`\\n\\nYou can skip this next step if you would rather connect to your RDS instance using a database tool to create the WordPress user and Database.\\n\\n`yum install mysql`\\n\\nWe will also want to install our FTP service.  For this tutorial we'll use vsftp:\\n\\n`yum install vsftpd`\\n\\nNow we will want to make sure when we turn on our instance that Apache is started, so let's run the following command:\\n\\n`chkconfig httpd on`\\n\\n## Configuring Our Software\\n\\nNow that we have everything we need installed, let's tweak some settings around.\\n\\n### HTTP\\n\\nFirst thing since WordPress uses index.php as its main entry point we will need to make sure Apache knows that.  Let's edit our Apache config by running the following:\\n\\n`vim /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf`\\n\\nFind the following block of code:\\n\\n*place holder*\\n\\nI've already added it here, but you will want to make sure index.php is added, otherwise Apache will not look to load it, and you're WordPress site won't load.\\n\\n### VSFTP\\n\\nHere we'll want to open our configuration file:\\n\\n`vim /etc/vsftpd/vsftpd.conf`\\n\\nWe will first want to uncomment and change \\\"chroot_local_user\\\" and change it \\\"chroot_local_user=YES\\\".  This will prevent our FTP user we're about to create from accessing our entire system.\\n\\nThere we will want to change \\\"anonymous_enable=YES\\\" to \\\"anonymous_enable=NO\\\". Then let's go down to the bottom of our file and add the following code:\\n\\n```\\npasv_enable=YES\\npasv_min_port=1024\\npasv_max_port=1048\\npasv_address=ec2instancePublicIP\\n```\\n\\nLet's save and restart the service:\\n\\n`/etc/init.d/vsftpd restart`\\n\\n### Creating our Linux User for Apache & FTP\\n\\nNow we're going to create a user which we will user for our WordPress site, to log into FTP.\\n\\n`adduser wpuser`\\n\\nThen we will set the password (make sure to save this) for our new user.\\n\\n`passwd wpuser`\\n\\nNow as mentioned before, we've prevent our ftp user from accessing our entire system, so we'll want to change its home directory. To do that we will run:\\n\\n`usermod -d /var/www/html/ wpuser`\\n\\nThis will set our wpuser home directory to the location where we will be serving our WordPress blog.\\n\\n## Downloading and Setting up WordPress\\n\\nHere we'll get our WordPress install to \\\"/var/www/html/\\\" and get our permissions setup.  First let's download the latest version of WordPress and extract it to our web folder:\\n\\n`wget https://wordpress.org/latest.tar.gz`\\n`tar -xzf latest.tar.gz`\\n\\nNow when we type ls we should see our \\\"wordpress\\\" folder. Let's move its contents into our html folder.\\n\\n`mv wordpress/* /var/www/html/`\\n\\nNow that we got it at the right location let's change directories there and start working on our site.\\n\\n`cd /var/www/html`\\n\\nNow that we're here we need to change permissions so that our user and apache can access this folder:\\n\\n`chown -R apache:apache /var/www/html`\\n\\nThis command will make wpuser the owner and change the group to apache.\\n\\n### Editing the WordPress Config\\n\\nNow that we have that let's make a copy of the wp-config-sample.php and bring it to our active config and edit it.\\n\\ncp wp-config-sample.php wp-config.php\\nvim wp-config.php\\n\\nThere are 4 variables that we'll be changing there.\\n\\n/** The name of the database for WordPress */\\ndefine('DB_NAME', 'wpblog');\\n\\n/** MySQL database username */\\ndefine('DB_USER', 'wpblogger');\\n\\n/** MySQL database password */\\ndefine('DB_PASSWORD', 'password');\\n\\n/** MySQL hostname */\\ndefine('DB_HOST', 'myrdsprivatehostname');\\nWe'll be create the user and password in just a sec, but you can grab myrdsprivatehostname (Endpoint) from the RDS page in the AWS console.\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}","page":false,"plaintext":"","slug":"wordpress-on-aws-part-3","status":"draft","title":"WordPress on AWS - Part 3","updated_at":"2018-01-03T22:11:29.000Z","updated_by":"1","tags":{},"author_id":"1"}}},"query":{"include":"tags"}},"res":{"_headers":{"x-powered-by":"Express","cache-control":"no-cache, private, no-store, must-revalidate, max-stale=0, post-check=0, pre-check=0","access-control-allow-origin":"https://bmonsalvatge.com","vary":"Origin, Accept-Encoding","x-cache-invalidate":"/p/628d6232-ea4c-41e1-822c-c6d3462b4c17/","content-type":"application/json; charset=utf-8","etag":"W/\"1a79-QOjyGjdRV4itGwJsV3US7Y+D3Wo\"","content-encoding":"gzip"},"statusCode":200,"responseTime":"150ms"},"msg":"","time":"2018-01-03T22:11:46.947Z","v":0}
{"name":"Log","hostname":"localhost","pid":16128,"level":30,"req":{"meta":{"requestId":"1c9b3970-f0d3-11e7-b951-c1a9cf7ca6a4","userId":"1"},"url":"/posts/5a4d5340fd55d33f00065ad5/?include=tags","method":"PUT","originalUrl":"/ghost/api/v0.1/posts/5a4d5340fd55d33f00065ad5/?include=tags","params":{"id":"5a4d5340fd55d33f00065ad5"},"headers":{"x-forwarded-for":"67.8.27.65","x-forwarded-proto":"https","x-real-ip":"67.8.27.65","host":"bmonsalvatge.com","connection":"close","content-length":"6046","origin":"https://bmonsalvatge.com","app-pragma":"no-cache","content-type":"application/json; charset=UTF-8","accept":"application/json, text/javascript, */*; q=0.01","x-requested-with":"XMLHttpRequest","x-ghost-version":"1.19","user-agent":"Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/63.0.3239.84 Safari/537.36","referer":"https://bmonsalvatge.com/ghost/","accept-encoding":"gzip, deflate, br","accept-language":"en-US,en;q=0.9"},"body":{"posts":{"0":{"id":"5a4d5340fd55d33f00065ad5","created_at":"2018-01-03T22:03:44.000Z","featured":false,"codeinjection_foot":"","codeinjection_head":"","mobiledoc":"{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"# Setting Up Our Web Instance\\n\\nWe will be configuring our web VM with Apache 2.4, PHP 7.0.  In addition, for simplicity, we will install the default MySQL package on our VM as this will allow us to later connect to our RDS instance and create the WP User and Database for our site.\\n\\nFirst let's SSH into our EC2 instance.  To do this you will need to grab the public IP, or public DNS, of your EC2 instance we just created.  You can do this by selecting your EC2 instance from the \\\"Instances\\\" tab on the left.  You can either drag or select those gray boxes on the right to make the bottom pane larger.\\n\\n*place holder*\\n\\nOnce you have your public IP let's SSH in!  from your favorite SSH tool run the following command (Terminal on Mac or Linux, and I recommend cmder on Windows):\\n\\n`ssh -i mykeylocation.pem ec2-user@mypublicipaddress`\\n\\nIf you're on a Mac you may get a warning about permissions.  To fix this you must run the follow command to change the permissions level of your private key:\\n\\n`chmod 400 mykeylocation.pem`\\n\\nOnce connect let's elevate to root privileges for this setup (we'll fix the permissions of our website specifically afterwards).\\n\\n`sudo su -`\\n\\n## Installing Software\\n\\nNow that we're logged in let's run the following commands to get all the necessary software onto our EC2 instance.\\n\\n`yum install httpd24`\\n`yum install php70`\\n`yum install php70-mysql*`\\n\\nYou can skip this next step if you would rather connect to your RDS instance using a database tool to create the WordPress user and Database.\\n\\n`yum install mysql`\\n\\nWe will also want to install our FTP service.  For this tutorial we'll use vsftp:\\n\\n`yum install vsftpd`\\n\\nNow we will want to make sure when we turn on our instance that Apache is started, so let's run the following command:\\n\\n`chkconfig httpd on`\\n\\n## Configuring Our Software\\n\\nNow that we have everything we need installed, let's tweak some settings around.\\n\\n### HTTP\\n\\nFirst thing since WordPress uses index.php as its main entry point we will need to make sure Apache knows that.  Let's edit our Apache config by running the following:\\n\\n`vim /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf`\\n\\nFind the following block of code:\\n\\n*place holder*\\n\\nI've already added it here, but you will want to make sure index.php is added, otherwise Apache will not look to load it, and you're WordPress site won't load.\\n\\n### VSFTP\\n\\nHere we'll want to open our configuration file:\\n\\n`vim /etc/vsftpd/vsftpd.conf`\\n\\nWe will first want to uncomment and change \\\"chroot_local_user\\\" and change it \\\"chroot_local_user=YES\\\".  This will prevent our FTP user we're about to create from accessing our entire system.\\n\\nThere we will want to change \\\"anonymous_enable=YES\\\" to \\\"anonymous_enable=NO\\\". Then let's go down to the bottom of our file and add the following code:\\n\\n```\\npasv_enable=YES\\npasv_min_port=1024\\npasv_max_port=1048\\npasv_address=ec2instancePublicIP\\n```\\n\\nLet's save and restart the service:\\n\\n`/etc/init.d/vsftpd restart`\\n\\n### Creating our Linux User for Apache & FTP\\n\\nNow we're going to create a user which we will user for our WordPress site, to log into FTP.\\n\\n`adduser wpuser`\\n\\nThen we will set the password (make sure to save this) for our new user.\\n\\n`passwd wpuser`\\n\\nNow as mentioned before, we've prevent our ftp user from accessing our entire system, so we'll want to change its home directory. To do that we will run:\\n\\n`usermod -d /var/www/html/ wpuser`\\n\\nThis will set our wpuser home directory to the location where we will be serving our WordPress blog.\\n\\n## Downloading and Setting up WordPress\\n\\nHere we'll get our WordPress install to \\\"/var/www/html/\\\" and get our permissions setup.  First let's download the latest version of WordPress and extract it to our web folder:\\n\\n`wget https://wordpress.org/latest.tar.gz`\\n`tar -xzf latest.tar.gz`\\n\\nNow when we type ls we should see our \\\"wordpress\\\" folder. Let's move its contents into our html folder.\\n\\n`mv wordpress/* /var/www/html/`\\n\\nNow that we got it at the right location let's change directories there and start working on our site.\\n\\n`cd /var/www/html`\\n\\nNow that we're here we need to change permissions so that our user and apache can access this folder:\\n\\n`chown -R apache:apache /var/www/html`\\n\\nThis command will make wpuser the owner and change the group to apache.\\n\\n### Editing the WordPress Config\\n\\nNow that we have that let's make a copy of the wp-config-sample.php and bring it to our active config and edit it.\\n\\n`cp wp-config-sample.php wp-config.php`\\n`vim wp-config.php`\\n\\nThere are 4 variables that we'll be changing there.\\n\\n/** The name of the database for WordPress */\\ndefine('DB_NAME', 'wpblog');\\n\\n/** MySQL database username */\\ndefine('DB_USER', 'wpblogger');\\n\\n/** MySQL database password */\\ndefine('DB_PASSWORD', 'password');\\n\\n/** MySQL hostname */\\ndefine('DB_HOST', 'myrdsprivatehostname');\\nWe'll be create the user and password in just a sec, but you can grab myrdsprivatehostname (Endpoint) from the RDS page in the AWS console.\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}","page":false,"plaintext":"","slug":"wordpress-on-aws-part-3","status":"draft","title":"WordPress on AWS - Part 3","updated_at":"2018-01-03T22:11:46.000Z","updated_by":"1","tags":{},"author_id":"1"}}},"query":{"include":"tags"}},"res":{"_headers":{"x-powered-by":"Express","cache-control":"no-cache, private, no-store, must-revalidate, max-stale=0, post-check=0, pre-check=0","access-control-allow-origin":"https://bmonsalvatge.com","vary":"Origin, Accept-Encoding","x-cache-invalidate":"/p/628d6232-ea4c-41e1-822c-c6d3462b4c17/","content-type":"application/json; charset=utf-8","etag":"W/\"1a93-FXF3XFzhvb+r7vpDa5dSQDNXi9Y\"","content-encoding":"gzip"},"statusCode":200,"responseTime":"118ms"},"msg":"","time":"2018-01-03T22:11:56.804Z","v":0}
