ng command (Terminal on Mac or Linux, and I recommend cmder on Windows):\\n\\n`ssh -i mykeylocation.pem ec2-user@mypublicipaddress`\\n\\nIf you're on a Mac you may get a warning about permissions.  To fix this you must run the follow command to change the permissions level of your private key:\\n\\n`chmod 400 mykeylocation.pem`\\n\\nOnce connect let's elevate to root privileges for this setup (we'll fix the permissions of our website specifically afterwards).\\n\\n`sudo su -`\\n\\n## Installing Software\\n\\nNow that we're logged in let's run the following commands to get all the necessary software onto our EC2 instance.\\n\\n`yum install httpd24`\\n`yum install php70`\\n`yum install php70-mysql*`\\n\\nYou can skip this next step if you would rather connect to your RDS instance using a database tool to create the WordPress user and Database.\\n\\n`yum install mysql`\\n\\nWe will also want to install our FTP service.  For this tutorial we'll use vsftp:\\n\\n`yum install vsftpd`\\n\\nNow we will want to make sure when we turn on our instance that Apache is started, so let's run the following command:\\n\\n`chkconfig httpd on`\\n\\n## Configuring Our Software\\n\\nNow that we have everything we need installed, let's tweak some settings around.\\n\\n### HTTP\\n\\nFirst thing since WordPress uses index.php as its main entry point we will need to make sure Apache knows that.  Let's edit our Apache config by running the following:\\n\\n`vim /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf`\\n\\nFind the following block of code:\\n\\n*place holder*\\n\\nI've already added it here, but you will want to make sure index.php is added, otherwise Apache will not look to load it, and you're WordPress site won't load.\\n\\n### VSFTP\\n\\nHere we'll want to open our configuration file:\\n\\n`vim /etc/vsftpd/vsftpd.conf`\\n\\nWe will first want to uncomment and change \\\"chroot_local_user\\\" and change it \\\"chroot_local_user=YES\\\".  This will prevent our FTP user we're about to create from accessing our entire system.\\n\\nThere we will want to change \\\"anonymous_enable=YES\\\" to \\\"anonymous_enable=NO\\\". Then let's go down to the bottom of our file and add the following code:\\n\\n```\\npasv_enable=YES\\npasv_min_port=1024\\npasv_max_port=1048\\npasv_address=ec2instancePublicIP\\n```\\n\\nLet's save and restart the service:\\n\\n`/etc/init.d/vsftpd restart`\\n\\n### Creating our Linux User for Apache & FTP\\n\\nNow we're going to create a user which we will user for our WordPress site, to log into FTP.\\n\\n`adduser wpuser`\\n\\nThen we will set the password (make sure to save this) for our new user.\\n\\n`passwd wpuser`\\n\\nNow as mentioned before, we've prevent our ftp user from accessing our entire system, so we'll want to change its home directory. To do that we will run:\\n\\n`usermod -d /var/www/html/ wpuser`\\n\\nThis will set our wpuser home directory to the location where we will be serving our WordPress blog.\\n\\n## Downloading and Setting up WordPress\\n\\nHere we'll get our WordPress install to \\\"/var/www/html/\\\" and get our permissions setup.  First let's download the latest version of WordPress and extract it to our web folder:\\n\\n`wget https://wordpress.org/latest.tar.gz`\\n`tar -xzf latest.tar.gz`\\n\\nNow when we type ls we should see our \\\"wordpress\\\" folder. Let's move its contents into our html folder.\\n\\n`mv wordpress/* /var/www/html/`\\n\\nNow that we got it at the right location let's change directories there and start working on our site.\\n\\n`cd /var/www/html`\\n\\nNow that we're here we need to change permissions so that our user and apache can access this folder:\\n\\n`chown -R apache:apache /var/www/html`\\n\\nThis command will make wpuser the owner and change the group to apache.\\n\\n### Editing the WordPress Config\\n\\nNow that we have that let's make a copy of the wp-config-sample.php and bring it to our active config and edit it.\\n\\n`cp wp-config-sample.php wp-config.php`\\n`vim wp-config.php`\\n\\nThere are 4 variables that we'll be changing there.\\n\\n```\\n/** The name of the database for WordPress */\\ndefine('DB_NAME', 'wpblog');\\n\\n/** MySQL database username */\\ndefine('DB_USER', 'wpblogger');\\n\\n/** MySQL database password */\\ndefine('DB_PASSWORD', 'password');\\n\\n/** MySQL hostname */\\ndefine('DB_HOST', 'myrdsprivatehostname');\\nWe'll be create the user and password in just a sec, but you can grab myrdsprivatehostname (Endpoint) from the RDS page in the AWS console.\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}","page":false,"plaintext":"","slug":"wordpress-on-aws-part-3","status":"draft","title":"WordPress on AWS - Part 3","updated_at":"2018-01-03T22:11:56.000Z","updated_by":"1","tags":{},"author_id":"1"}}},"query":{"include":"tags"}},"res":{"_headers":{"x-powered-by":"Express","cache-control":"no-cache, private, no-store, must-revalidate, max-stale=0, post-check=0, pre-check=0","access-control-allow-origin":"https://bmonsalvatge.com","vary":"Origin, Accept-Encoding","x-cache-invalidate":"/p/628d6232-ea4c-41e1-822c-c6d3462b4c17/","content-type":"application/json; charset=utf-8","etag":"W/\"1a81-Y5KEc/IfxdhlBskVzogr2usIpR0\"","content-encoding":"gzip"},"statusCode":200,"responseTime":"119ms"},"msg":"","time":"2018-01-03T22:12:11.428Z","v":0}
